{"id":"1809.02158","submitter":"Enrique Rodriguez-Fernandez","authors":"Enrique Rodriguez-Fernandez and Rodolfo Cuerno","title":"Gaussian statistics as an emergent symmetry of the stochastic Burgers\n  equation","comments":"6 pages, 3 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. E 99, 042108 (2019)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevE.99.042108","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.stat-mech cond-mat.dis-nn cond-mat.quant-gas nlin.AO physics.data-an","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Symmetries play a conspicuous role in the large-scale behavior of critical\nsystems. While in equilibrium they allow to classify asymptotics into different\nuniversality classes, out of equilibrium they can emerge, some times\nunexpectedly, as collective properties which are not explicit in the 'bare'\ninteractions. Here we elucidate the emergence of an up-down symmetry in the\nasymptotic behavior of the stochastic scalar Burgers equation in one and two\ndimensions, manifested by the occurrence of Gaussian fluctuations for the\nphysical field. This robustness of Gaussian behavior contradicts naive\nexpectations, due to the detailed relation ---including the same set of\nsymmetries--- between Burgers equation and the Kardar-Parisi-Zhang equation,\nwhich paradigmatically displays non-Gaussian fluctuations described by\nTracy-Widom distributions. We reach our conclusions via a dynamic\nrenormalization group study of the field statistics, confirmed by direct\nevaluation of the field probability distribution function from numerical\nsimulations of the dynamical equation. All odd-order cumulants cancel exactly,\nwhile the excess kurtosis vanishes for large systems, indeed consistent with\nGaussian behavior.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 6 Sep 2018 18:27:15 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 25 Apr 2019 13:34:19 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-04-26"}
